            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the Caesar cipher works</h2>
              <p>
                The Caesar cipher (also called a shift cipher) is a substitution
                cipher where each letter in the message is replaced by another
                letter a fixed number of positions down the alphabet.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="mono mb-1">E(x) = (x + k) mod 26</p>
                <p class="mono">D(x) = (x − k) mod 26</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mt-1">
                  where <span class="mono">x</span> is the letter index (A=0,
                  B=1, …, Z=25) and <span class="mono">k</span> is the shift
                  (key).
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>For example, with a shift of <strong>3</strong>:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>A → D, B → E, C → F, …, X → A, Y → B, Z → C</li>
                <li>
                  <span class="mono">HELLO</span> becomes
                  <span class="mono">KHOOR</span>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Encryption vs decryption</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Encrypt (encode):</strong> add the shift to each
                  letter index.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Decrypt (decode):</strong> subtract the shift from
                  each letter index.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                A negative shift is equivalent to shifting in the opposite
                direction. For example, shift −3 is the same as shift 23.
              </p>

              <h2>Using this Caesar cipher tool</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Choose a <strong>mode</strong>: encrypt, decrypt, brute‑force,
                  or auto‑crack.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter or adjust the <strong>shift</strong> (key) when in
                  encrypt/decrypt mode.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Select an <strong>alphabet</strong> or define your own custom
                  alphabet.
                </li>
                <li>Paste or type your <strong>input text</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Run Caesar cipher”</strong> to see the result.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Brute‑force and auto‑crack</h3>
              <p>
                Because there are only 25 non‑trivial keys for the classic A–Z
                Caesar cipher, it is easy to break:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Brute‑force:</strong> tries all possible shifts and
                  shows every candidate plaintext.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Auto‑crack:</strong> uses
                  <strong>frequency analysis</strong> for the selected language
                  to score each shift and rank the most likely plaintexts.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Security considerations</h2>
              <p>
                The Caesar cipher is <strong>not secure</strong> for real‑world
                use. It can be broken instantly by trying all shifts or by
                simple statistical analysis. It is valuable as a teaching tool
                and for puzzles, escape rooms, or games, but never for
                protecting sensitive information.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can this tool handle numbers and punctuation?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. By default, letters are shifted and all other characters
                (spaces, digits, punctuation, emojis) are left unchanged. If you
                choose the <strong>digits</strong> alphabet or define a
                <strong>custom alphabet</strong> that includes digits or
                symbols, those characters will also be shifted.
              </p>

              <h3>What is the difference between Caesar cipher and ROT13?</h3>
              <p>
                ROT13 is a special case of the Caesar cipher with a fixed shift
                of 13 on the 26‑letter Latin alphabet. Applying ROT13 twice
                returns the original text. With this tool you can reproduce
                ROT13 by setting the shift to 13.
              </p>

              <h3>Why do some brute‑force results look like gibberish?</h3>
              <p>
                Only one shift corresponds to the original plaintext; the other
                25 shifts are usually nonsense. The auto‑crack mode helps by
                ranking the shifts that most closely match typical letter
                frequencies in the chosen language.
              </p>
